"Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thorpe","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire and Lancashire): from Middle English <i>thorp(e)</i> ‘village, hamlet, farmstead’ (Old Norse, Old English <i>thorp</i> ‘secondary settlement’). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in such a settlement, or habitational, for someone from any of several places called Thorp(e), which are most frequent in Yorkshire, the Midlands, and East Anglia. Compare   Throop  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Trupp","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Hermann, Reinhold.","English (Herefordshire and Monmouthshire): variant of   Thorpe  , or from a place so named, such as Thrupp (Berkshire, Gloucestershire, Oxfordshire), Thrupe (Somerset), Throop (Dorset, Hampshire, Somerset), and Throope (Wiltshire).","Altered form of German   Trapp  ."]},{"name":"Throop","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>throp</i> ‘village, hamlet, farmstead’ (Old Norse, Old English <i>throp</i> ‘secondary settlement’). The surname may be topographic, for someone who lived in such a settlement, or habitational, for someone from Throop in Hampshire, Throope in Wiltshire, Thrup in Oxfordshire, or any of the places called Thrupp in Berkshire, Gloucestershire, and Northamptonshire. Compare   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharpe","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Thorpe  . This form of the surname is rare in Britain and Ireland."]},{"name":"Thorp","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire and Lancashire): variant of   Thorpe  .","Scandinavian: variant of   Torp  ."]},{"name":"Troup","meanings":["Scottish (eastern): habitational name from a place in the parish of Gamrie, near Banff. The placename is unexplained, perhaps a Pictish cognate of Welsh <i>trwp</i> ‘vessel, dish, basin’.","Possibly also English, a metathesized form of   Thorpe  ."]},{"name":"Tharp","meanings":["English: variant of   Thorpe  ."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: The Scripture name, in Hebrew, Adham, signifying 'man;' literally earthy, red earth; Rudolph, however, says the name in Ethiopic means ' to be fair, beautiful.' Hence the nurse-name Addy, little Adam."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":9,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":18,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705195,"age":63,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Adam Thorpe was born about 1319, in Nottinghamshire, England, his father, Sir William De Thorpe, was -70 and his mother, Margaret De Thorpe, was -71. He married Adam about 1345, in Nottinghamshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"about 1319–":"umbes 1319–Surnud","1319–Male":"1319–Surnud","1325–Female":"1325–Surnud","1348–Female":"1348–Surnud","1390–1319":"1390–1319","1391–1350":"1391–1350","1348":"1348","1337":"1337","1325":"1325","about 1319":"umbes 1319","1453":"1453","about 1345":"umbes 1345","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","1391":"1391",